<h1>Images &amp; Lists :Class notes</h1>
<p>More Chapter 5 stuff </p>
<p>Adding images to your web site. </p>
<p>Types of image formats</p>
<ol>
  <li>GIF - Graphics Interchange Format (.gif) Transparent background possible. 
  Animated GIFs</li>
  <li>JPEG or JPG - Joint Photographics Experts Group (.jpg or .jpeg) Better 
  photographic quality color than GIF</li>
  <li>PNG - Portable Network Graphics (.png) New, supported by most but not all 
  NEWER browsers. Still developing. </li>
  <li>SVG- Scalable Vector Graphic (.svg)&nbsp; Released 2001 mathematically 
  based, xml complient.</li>
  <li>PDF - Portable Data Format (.pdf) Cannot be read by current browser. </li>
  <li>TIFF -Tagged Image File Format commonly used across platforms (.tif on MS 
  .tiff on Apple &amp; Unix)</li>
  <li>BMP - Bit-Mapped Picture (.bmp) Standard Windows image format.<br>
&nbsp;</li>
</ol>
<p>So, what format is the best?&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Image file sizes and download time . </p>
<p>Suppose you had a 600 pixel x 300 pixel image or 180,000 pixels. If we used a 
file format with 8 bits per pixel, we would have to download a </p>
<p>1,440,000 bit file. Point is, the more images the slower the download time!</p>
<p>Image tag<br>
<br>
<b>&lt;img&gt; &lt;/img&gt;</b>&nbsp; OR use</p>
<p><b>&lt;img/&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>Important attributes</b></p>
<ul>
  <li><b>src </b>- source attribute - needed to identify the file name (including 
  extension) and path to image.</li>
  <li><b>alt</b> - alternative text - used to identify what image will be displayed 
  if image is not displayed. Also, identifies the image when mouse rests over 
  image.</li>
</ul>
