<p>Yes, you guessed it. LISTS!!</p>
<p>There are Three basic list types</p>
<ol>
  <li>Ordered list</li>
  <li>Unordered list</li>
  <li>Definition list</li>
</ol>
<p><b>Ordered list</b><br>
<br>
Yes, new tags.</p>
<p><b>&lt;ol&gt; &lt;/ol&gt; to declare the list</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;li&gt; &lt;/li&gt; to define the list items</b></p>
<p><b>example - this will provide a numerical list (list can also be Alpha). 
However, both list are increasing.</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;ol&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;li&gt; list item #1 &lt;/li&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;li&gt; list item #2 &lt;/li&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;li&gt; list item #2 &lt;/li&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;/ol&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;ul&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; to declare the list</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;li&gt; &lt;/li&gt; to define the list items</b></p>
<p><b>example - this will provide a bulleted list.</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;ul&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;li&gt; list item #1 &lt;/li&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;li&gt; list item #2 &lt;/li&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;li&gt; list item #2 &lt;/li&gt;</b></p>
<p><b>&lt;/ul&gt;</b></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>These list can be nested so PLEASE make use of an indenting style when 
coding!!</p>
